      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A memory leak in an automotive control unit is a serious issue, especially when it can cause the system to crash. You can start by using a memory debugging tool, such as Valgrind or AddressSanitizer, to help identify the source of the leak. These tools can analyze your code and report any memory-related issues, including memory leaks and incorrect memory usage.\n\nTo systematically find the leak, you can try the following steps:\n\n1. **Instrument your code**: Add logging statements to track memory allocations and deallocations. This will help you identify where memory is being allocated and deallocated, which can give you a clue about where the leak is happening.\n2. **Use a memory leak detector**: There are several libraries available that can help detect memory leaks, such as Newlib or Memory Leak Detector. These libraries can track memory allocations and deallocations, and alert you when a memory leak is detected.\n3. **Profile your code**: Use a profiling tool, such as gprof or Intel VTune Amplifier, to analyze the performance of your code. This can help you identify which functions are using the most memory, which can give you a clue about where the leak is happening.\n4. **Review your code**: Go through your code and",
